This paper develops a model to depict the interplay between child mortality, fertility and working hours. 
In it, parents partially control their children's chances of survival through their expenditure on food, medicines, etc. 
Due to this assumption, having a child increases the household's demand for goods, and thus, the supply of labour along the intensive margin. 
By contrast, improvements in child mortality lead parents to raise fewer children and invest more in their education. 
The combination of these two mechanisms implies then that demographic transitions come along with trends in the use of time as those observed since the Industrial Revolution.
